SUMMARY:POSTPONED: Unsung Black Artists of Antebellum Era NEW
DESCRIPTION:This is a free Adult School class has been postponed due to an 
 unexpected instructior schedule conflict. An new date will be announced 
 soon.\n\nRegistration is required. Click here to register.\n\nDespite the 
 trauma of enslavement\, racism and segregation African American artists had 
 their own forms of art. Join Onnie Strother to explore how Black artists 
 before Emancipation created\, pottery\, quilts\, paintings and 
 photographs\, which forged a tradition of creativity and\nexcellence for 
 future generations to follow. Among others\, we'll survey the life and work 
 of Augustus Washington\, Photographer\; Henry Ossawa Tanner\, Painter\; 
 Grafton Brown\, Painter\; Edmonia Lewis\, Sculptor\; and David Drake\, 
 Potter.\n\nMade possible by funds from the New Jersey State Council on the 
 Arts\, a partner agency of the National Endowment for the Arts.\n\n
LOCATION:Montclair Public Library
ORGANIZER;CN="Montclair Adult School":MAILTO:adultschool@montclairlibrary.org
CATEGORIES:Adult School
UID:LibCal-10306-15827591
URL:https://bccls.libcal.com/event/15827591
